"Card data theft is still happening, so the third revision of the PCI Data Security Standard is as much a re-launch as a revamp. Many organisations – even Level 1 merchants – have yet to fully implement all requirements of the PCI DSS V2 or previous versions of the standard, so eyes may well be rolling at a new version of a standard which hasn't yet been mastered in its previous forms. This new version is more about refinement and clarification than any introduction of new techniques or technologies to help protect against card data theft, but while losses through card fraud are still on the increase, it is clear that something has to change. The third revision of the PCI Data Security Standard is as much a re-launch as a revamp. Yet many organisations – even Level 1 merchants – have yet to fully implement all requirements of previous versions of the standard. This new version is more about refinement and clarification than any introduction of new techniques or technologies to help protect against card data theft. But while losses through card fraud are still on the increase, it is clear that something has to change, explains Mark Kedgley of New Net Technologies."
